\backslash
subsection*{The Scalable Language}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

The name "Scala" comes from 
\backslash
textit{SCAlable LAnguage}.
 This refers to the language's ability to create small,
 "internal" Domain Specific Languages (DSLs).
 This is why libraries like 
\backslash
texttt{sttp} and 
\backslash
texttt{Doobie} feel like they are part of the language itself rather than external additions.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
subsection*{Unified Type System}
\end_layout

\begin_layout Plain Layout

Unlike Java,
 which has "primitive" types (like 
\backslash
texttt{int}) and "objects" (like 
\backslash
texttt{Integer}),
 Scala treats everything as an object.
 However,
 the compiler is smart enough to optimize these down to primitives under the hood to ensure there is no performance penalty.
\end_layout

